SIMPLE: mask
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mask
<hw>Mask</hw> <pr>(m⟦adot⟧sk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>masque</ets>, LL. <ets>masca</ets>, <ets>mascha</ets>,
<ets>mascus</ets>; cf. Sp. & Pg. <ets>m⟦aacute⟧scara</ets>, It.
<ets>maschera</ets>; all fr. Ar. <ets>maskharat</ets> buffoon, fool,
pleasantry, anything ridiculous or mirthful, fr. <ets>sakhira</ets> to
ridicule, to laugh at. Cf. <er>Masque</er>, <er>Masquerade</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A cover, or partial cover, for the face, used for
disguise or protection; <as>as, a dancer's <ex>mask</ex>; a fencer's
<ex>mask</ex>; a ball player's <ex>mask</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which disguises; a pretext or
subterfuge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A festive entertainment of dancing or other
diversions, where all wear masks; a masquerade; hence, a revel; a
frolic; a delusive show.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This thought might lead me through the world's vain
<qex>mask</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A dramatic performance, formerly in vogue, in which
the actors wore masks and represented mythical or allegorical
characters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A grotesque head or face, used to
adorn keystones and other prominent parts, to spout water in fountains,
and the like; -- called also <altname>mascaron</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>In a permanent
fortification, a redoubt which protects the caponiere.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A screen for a battery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The lower lip of the larva of a
dragon fly, modified so as to form a prehensile organ.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A person wearing a mask; a masker.</def></p>

<p><q>The <qex>mask</qex> that has the arm of the Indian queen.</q>
<rj><qau>G. W. Cable.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Sporting)</fld> <def>The head or face of a
fox.</def></p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mask house</b></col>, <cd>a house for masquerades.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs> -- <col><b>Death mask</b></col>, <cd>a cast of
the face of a dead person.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mask</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mask
<hw>Mask</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Masked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Masking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover, as the
face, by way of concealment or defense against injury; to conceal with a
mask or visor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They must all be <qex>masked</qex> and vizarded.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To disguise; to cover; to hide.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Masking</qex> the business from the common eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To conceal; also, to
intervene in the line of.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To cover or keep in
check; <as>as, to <ex>mask</ex> a body of troops or a fortress by a
superior force, while some hostile evolution is being carried
out</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mask</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mask
<hw>Mask</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take part as a
masker in a masquerade.</def> <rj><au>Cavendish.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wear a mask; to be disguised in any way.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masked</ent>⟦br⟧
